15,"button_padding_tb":10,"button_padding_lr":25,"button_border_radius":50,"link_text":"LEARN LAYERING","link":"https:\/\/www.pearlizumi.com\/pages\/how-to-choose-the-right-cycling-base-layer","open_in_blank":false}},"sp_faq_gXMXdE":{"type":"sp-faq","blocks":{"question_Ani7tr":{"type":"question","settings":{"question":"Do I need bib tights or regular tights?","answer":"<p><strong>Bib tights<\/strong> stay put with straps, remove waistband pressure, and seal the gap between jersey and tightâ€”making them ideal for longer rides and colder conditions. <strong>Regular tights<\/strong> are quicker to pull on\/off, layer easily over padded shorts, and work well for commuting or mixed-use. Think distance and temperature: the longer and colder it gets, the more bibs make sense.<\/p>","is_open":true}},"question_c3dwxc":{"type":"question","settings":{"question":"Should I choose tights with or without a chamois?","answer":"<p>If youâ€™re riding long miles, a <strong>built-in chamois<\/strong> adds critical comfort and stability. Our Levitateâ„¢ family is designed to reduce friction, cushion where needed, and stay steady as the ride wears on. <strong>No-chamois tights<\/strong> are better if you want to layer over padded shorts, use the same tight for commuting and the gym, or prefer flexibility in how you build your kit.<\/p>","is_open":false}},"question_At7Vnc":{"type":"question","settings":{"question":"What temperature ranges are Thermal vs. AmFIBÂ® tights designed for?","answer":"<p><strong>Thermal tights<\/strong> are your everyday cold-weather gearâ€”best around <strong>34â€“45Â°F<\/strong>, where warmth and breathability need to balance. <strong>AmFIBÂ® tights<\/strong> add windproof softshell panels, making them the pick for <strong>sub-freezing rides, strong wind, or sleet<\/strong>. Intensity and layering matter too: harder efforts or more base layers shift the range.<\/p>","is_open":false}},"question_7hbRD8":{"type":"question","settings":{"question":"How should winter tights fit?","answer":"<p>They should feel <strong>supportive, not restrictive<\/strong>. Expect light compression through the legs, no sag at the knee, and straps that lie flat without digging. A proper fit disappears once youâ€™re pedalingâ€”no shifting, no bunching, just steady warmth and motion. If youâ€™re between sizes, inseam length and strap comfort should guide the choice.<\/p>","is_open":false}},"question_TrpKxe":{"type":"question","settings":{"question":"Are these tights water-resistant or waterproof?","answer":"<p>Most winter tights are <strong>water-resistant, not fully waterproof<\/strong>. Finishes like <strong>PI DryÂ®<\/strong> bead off road spray and light rain without affecting stretch or breathability. For full waterproofing, look to our <strong>WxB jackets and shells<\/strong>, but for legs, water-shedding tights are the sweet spot: they block grime and stay comfortable without trapping heat.<\/p>","is_open":false}},"question_NQCqgw":{"type":"question","settings":{"question":"How do womenâ€™s bib tights handle bathroom breaks?","answer":"<p>Select womenâ€™s bib tights feature <strong>drop-tail designs or smart-strap systems<\/strong> that make nature breaks quick and low-stress. That means no removing layers, gloves, or jacketsâ€”just ride-ready function designed for real-world stops. Check the product details to confirm if the feature is included.<\/p>","is_open":false}},"question_fmwwA7":{"type":"question","settings":{"question":"How do I care for tights with special finishes like PI DryÂ® or AmFIBÂ®?","answer":"<p>Wash cold, use mild detergent, and skip fabric softenersâ€”they can clog performance finishes. Hang dry whenever possible to protect stretch and the chamois. For water-repellent fabrics like <strong>PI DryÂ®<\/strong>, a low tumble-dry cycle can help reactivate the finish. Treated right, your tights will hold their weather protection and fit season after season.<\/p>","is_open":false}}},"block_order":["question_Ani7tr","question_c